2026-03-30 | Minimum Cost to Connect All Houses

	Question
Return minimum cost to connect all houses.

	Approach (Prim’s Algorithm)
1.	Start from any node (say 0).  
2.	Maintain:
		minDist[i] → minimum cost to connect node i  
3.	At each step:
		pick node with smallest connection cost  
4.	Update distances of remaining nodes  
5.	Sum all selected edge costs  

	Time Complexity
	O(n²)

	Space Complexity
	O(n)

	Solution

class Solution {
public:
    int minCostConnectPoints(vector<vector<int>>& points) {

        int n = points.size();
        vector<int> minDist(n, INT_MAX);
        vector<bool> used(n, false);

        minDist[0] = 0;
        int totalCost = 0;

        for(int i = 0; i < n; i++){

            int u = -1;

            for(int j = 0; j < n; j++){
                if(!used[j] && (u == -1 || minDist[j] < minDist[u])){
                    u = j;
                }
            }

            used[u] = true;
            totalCost += minDist[u];

            for(int v = 0; v < n; v++){
                if(!used[v]){
                    int dist = abs(points[u][0] - points[v][0]) +
                               abs(points[u][1] - points[v][1]);

                    minDist[v] = min(minDist[v], dist);
                }
            }
        }

        return totalCost;
    }
};

	Key Insight
This is a **complete graph** (every pair has an edge).  
Using Prim’s algorithm avoids building all edges explicitly.  

We greedily connect the closest unconnected house each time → optimal MST.
